body:
This code 
```rust
macro_rules! line {
    () => {
        Some(lines)
    };
}

fn main() {
    Some(Some(())).map(|line!()| line.unwrap());
}

```

([Playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=9a59569959f7a17dced3f05fc16bc34f))

Gives output:

```
   Compiling playground v0.0.1 (/playground)
error[E0423]: expected value, found macro `line`
 --> src/main.rs:8:34
  |
8 |     Some(Some(())).map(|line!()| line.unwrap());
  |                                  ^^^^
  |
help: a local variable with a similar name exists
  |
8 |     Some(Some(())).map(|line!()| lines.unwrap());
  |                                  ^^^^^
help: use `!` to invoke the macro
  |
8 |     Some(Some(())).map(|line!()| line!.unwrap());
  |                                  ^^^^^

error: aborting due to previous error

For more information about this error, try `rustc --explain E0423`.
error: could not compile `playground`.

To learn more, run the command again with --verbose.

```
- Second hint `help: use ! to invoke the macro` is incorrect because it proposes to write code `line!.unwrap()`.
- First hint says that `help: a local variable with a similar name exists` but doesn't print this name and only shows generated output, so it can be difficult for user to understand what happens if, for ex., macro defined in other lib/module or if statement looks like
```rust
let lines = Some(Some(())).map(|line!()| line.unwrap());
```
